  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law and national laws on money laundering intersect in several key ways:\n\n1. International Conventions and Treaties\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Provide frameworks for combating money laundering\n- Establish common standards and guidelines\n\n2. Mutual Legal Assistance\n- Countries collaborate on investigations\n- Share financial intelligence\n- Extradite suspects\n- Enforce cross-border legal proceedings\n\n3. Regulatory Harmonization\n- Standardized reporting requirements\n- Similar legal definitions of money laundering\n- Consistent due diligence protocols\n- Enhanced international financial transparency\n\n4. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Banks and financial institutions required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) procedures\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- International information sharing\n\n5. Enforcement Cooperation\n- Joint investigations\n- Coordinated asset seizures\n- Multilateral law enforcement networks\n- Interpol and other international agencies\n\n6. Sanctions and Penalties\n- Coordinated economic sanctions\n- Targeted financial restrictions\n- Penalties for non-compliance\n- International financial monitoring\n\nThese intersections create a complex, interconnected system for preventing and prosecuting money laundering globally.",
